[
  {
    "id": "page_0353-b001",
    "page_key": 353,
    "order": 1,
    "type": "heading",
    "text": "18.2.1 Diffusion kernel",
    "source": "deepseek+paddle",
    "confidence": "medium"
  },
  {
    "id": "page_0353-b002",
    "page_key": 353,
    "order": 2,
    "type": "paragraph",
    "text": "To train the decoder to invert this process, we use multiple samples $\\mathbf{z}_{t}$ at time $t$ for the same example $\\mathbf{x}$. However, generating these sequentially using equation 18.1 is time-consuming when $t$ is large. Fortunately, there is a closed-form expression for $q(\\mathbf{z}_{t}|\\mathbf{x})$, which allows us to directly draw samples $\\mathbf{z}_{1} \\ldots \\mathbf{z}_{t-1}$. This is known as the diffusion kernel (figure 18.3).",
    "source": "deepseek",
    "confidence": "medium"
  },
  {
    "id": "page_0353-b003",
    "page_key": 353,
    "order": 3,
    "type": "paragraph",
    "text": "To derive an expression for $q(\\mathbf{z}_{t}|\\mathbf{x})$, consider the first two steps of the forward process:",
    "source": "deepseek",
    "confidence": "medium"
  },
  {
    "id": "page_0353-b004",
    "page_key": 353,
    "order": 4,
    "type": "equation",
    "text": "$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n\\mathbf{z}_{1}&=\\sqrt{1-\\beta_{1}}\\cdot\\mathbf{x}+\\sqrt{\\beta_{1}}\\cdot\\boldsymbol{\\epsilon}_{1}\\\\\n\\mathbf{z}_{2}&=\\sqrt{1-\\beta_{2}}\\cdot\\mathbf{z}_{1}+\\sqrt{\\beta_{2}}\\cdot\\boldsymbol{\\epsilon}_{2}.\n\\end{aligned}\n\\qquad (18.4)\n$$",
    "source": "deepseek",
    "confidence": "medium"
  },
  {
    "id": "page_0353-b005",
    "page_key": 353,
    "order": 5,
    "type": "paragraph",
    "text": "Substituting the first equation into the second, we get:",
    "source": "deepseek",
    "confidence": "medium"
  },
  {
    "id": "page_0353-b006",
    "page_key": 353,
    "order": 6,
    "type": "equation",
    "text": "$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n\\mathbf{z}_{2}\\quad&=\\quad\\sqrt{1-\\beta_{2}}\\left(\\sqrt{1-\\beta_{1}\\cdot\\mathbf{x}}+\\sqrt{\\beta_{1}\\cdot\\boldsymbol{\\epsilon}_{1}}\\right)+\\sqrt{\\beta_{2}\\cdot\\boldsymbol{\\epsilon}_{2}}\\\\\n&=\\quad\\sqrt{1-\\beta_{2}}\\left(\\sqrt{1-\\beta_{1}\\cdot\\mathbf{x}}+\\sqrt{1-(1-\\beta_{1})\\cdot\\boldsymbol{\\epsilon}_{1}}\\right)+\\sqrt{\\beta_{2}\\cdot\\boldsymbol{\\epsilon}_{2}}\\\\\n&=\\quad\\sqrt{(1-\\beta_{2})(1-\\beta_{1})\\cdot\\mathbf{x}}+\\sqrt{1-\\beta_{2}-(1-\\beta_{2})(1-\\beta_{1})\\cdot\\boldsymbol{\\epsilon}_{1}}+\\sqrt{\\beta_{2}\\cdot\\boldsymbol{\\epsilon}_{2}}.\n\\end{aligned}\n\\qquad (18.5)\n$$",
    "source": "deepseek",
    "confidence": "medium"
  },
  {
    "id": "page_0353-b007",
    "page_key": 353,
    "order": 7,
    "type": "paragraph",
    "text": "The last two terms are independent samples from mean-zero normal distributions with variances $1 - \\beta_{2} - (1 - \\beta_{2})(1 - \\beta_{1})$ and $\\beta_{2}$, respectively. The mean of this sum is zero, and its variance is the sum of the component variances (see problem 18.2), so:",
    "source": "deepseek",
    "confidence": "medium"
  },
  {
    "id": "page_0353-b008",
    "page_key": 353,
    "order": 8,
    "type": "paragraph",
    "text": "(18.6)",
    "source": "deepseek",
    "confidence": "medium"
  },
  {
    "id": "page_0353-b009",
    "page_key": 353,
    "order": 9,
    "type": "equation",
    "text": "$$\n\\mathbf{z}_{2}\\quad=\\quad\\sqrt{(1-\\beta_{2})(1-\\beta_{1})\\cdot\\mathbf{x}}+\\sqrt{1-(1-\\beta_{2})(1-\\beta_{1})}\\cdot\\boldsymbol{\\epsilon}\n\\qquad (18.6)\n$$",
    "source": "deepseek",
    "confidence": "medium"
  },
  {
    "id": "page_0353-b010",
    "page_key": 353,
    "order": 10,
    "type": "paragraph",
    "text": "where $\\epsilon$ is also a sample from a standard normal distribution.",
    "source": "deepseek",
    "confidence": "medium"
  },
  {
    "id": "page_0353-b011",
    "page_key": 353,
    "order": 11,
    "type": "paragraph",
    "text": "If we continue this process by substituting this equation into the expression for $\\mathbf{z}_{3}$ and so on, we can show that:",
    "source": "deepseek",
    "confidence": "medium"
  },
  {
    "id": "page_0353-b012",
    "page_key": 353,
    "order": 12,
    "type": "paragraph",
    "text": "(18.6)",
    "source": "deepseek",
    "confidence": "medium"
  },
  {
    "id": "page_0353-b013",
    "page_key": 353,
    "order": 13,
    "type": "equation",
    "text": "$$\n\\mathbf{z}_{t}=\\sqrt{\\alpha_{t}}\\cdot\\mathbf{x}+\\sqrt{1-\\alpha_{t}}\\cdot\\boldsymbol{\\epsilon}\n\\qquad (18.7)\n$$",
    "source": "deepseek",
    "confidence": "medium"
  },
  {
    "id": "page_0353-b014",
    "page_key": 353,
    "order": 14,
    "type": "paragraph",
    "text": "where $\\alpha_{t}=\\prod_{s=1}^{t}1-\\beta_{s}$. We can equivalently write this in probabilistic form:",
    "source": "deepseek",
    "confidence": "medium"
  },
  {
    "id": "page_0353-b015",
    "page_key": 353,
    "order": 15,
    "type": "equation",
    "text": "$$\nq(\\mathbf{z}_{t}|\\mathbf{x})=\\mathrm{Norm}_{\\mathbf{z}_{t}}\\left[\\sqrt{\\alpha_{t}\\cdot\\mathbf{x}},(1-\\alpha_{t})\\mathbf{I}\\right]\n\\qquad (18.8)\n$$",
    "source": "deepseek",
    "confidence": "medium"
  },
  {
    "id": "page_0353-b016",
    "page_key": 353,
    "order": 16,
    "type": "paragraph",
    "text": "For any starting data point x, variable $z_{t}$ is normally distributed with a known mean and variance. Consequently, if we don't care about the history of the evolution through the intermediate variables $z_{1} \\ldots z_{t-1}$ , it is easy to generate samples from $q(\\mathbf{z}_{t}|\\mathbf{x})$ .",
    "source": "deepseek",
    "confidence": "medium"
  },
  {
    "id": "page_0353-b017",
    "page_key": 353,
    "order": 17,
    "type": "heading",
    "text": "18.2.2 Marginal distributions",
    "source": "deepseek+paddle",
    "confidence": "medium"
  },
  {
    "id": "page_0353-b018",
    "page_key": 353,
    "order": 18,
    "type": "paragraph",
    "text": "The marginal distribution $q(\\mathbf{z}_{t})$ is the probability of observing a value of $\\mathbf{z}_{t}$ given the distribution of possible starting points $x$ and the possible diffusion paths for each starting",
    "source": "deepseek",
    "confidence": "medium"
  }
]
